                  <handDesc>
                     
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Hand a: fine and careful; hand b: fine; hand c: mediocre
                           and careless.</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red</seg>
                        <date>First half of the 19th century (?)</date>
                        <list type="abbreviations">
                           <item>Some of the abbreviations used throughout the texts:</item>
                           <item>፤ዕ፤ for ?</item>
                           <item>ለዓ፡ for ለዓለመ፡</item>
                           <item>ሃ፡ for ሃሌሉያ፡</item>
                           <item>
                              <abbr>Repeated versicles are often written in an abbreviated form,
                                 e.g., ፤ቅ፤ stands</abbr> for <expan>ቅዱስ፡ እግዚአብሔር፡ ቅዱስ፡ ኃያል፡ ቅዱስ፡ ሕያው
                              </expan> (e.g., <locus target="#1ra">1ra</locus>b).</item>
                        </list>
                        <seg type="rubrication">Nomina sacra; elements of the punctuation signs;
                           Ethiopic numerals or their elements.
 Text I
 Two initial lines
                           alternating with a black line in the incipit page; two initial lines
                           alternating with a black line of the incipit of Texts I-3 and I-4; names
                           of supplications, antiphons and chants (e.g., mastabqʷǝʿ, mǝlṭān, ʾǝsma
                           la-ʿālam, ʾaryām); initial words of supplications, antiphons and other
                           chants, and their sections (e.g., säbbǝḥǝwwo, kʷǝllomu, gǝnäyu,
                           nǝsebbǝḥo, ʾantä, sǝmaʿnni); names of feasts and other occasions; musical
                           notation: intratextual signs (e.g., ʾaryām qadāmi zema), interlinear
                           signs(e.g., fols.1ra, ) and elements of marginal signs; directives for
                           the ministers (e.g., yǝbäl). 
 Text II
 Names of antiphons
                           (mawāśǝʾt); names of sections of antiphons (mǝlṭān and mazmur); name of a
                           Dǝggʷā antiphon (ʾǝsma la-ʿālam); initial word of a Dǝggʷā antiphon
                           (yǝbarǝkǝwwo); intratextual musical notation sign (ʾaryām qadāmi zema);
                           word ṣalot “prayer”; chains of red and black dots separating groups of
                           antiphons belonging to different feasts.</seg>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">Hand a: <locus target="#1r">1r-</locus>v l.6, rounded, very regular
                        script</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic"> Hand b: <locus from="2ra" to="5vb">2ra-5vb</locus>, 37rv, slender script with slightly left sloping
                        letters</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic"> Hand c: <locus target="#1va">1va</locus> l.6-1vb, 6ra-36vb, rubrication and musical notation signs
                        throughout the Ms.; irregular, angular letters;
                        hearlines.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <list>
                        <item xml:id="e1">- An ownership note (?): <locus target="#13r">fol.  13r</locus>. - Passages omitted in the main text are written in the margins, by hand b: fols. 1ra, 4vb, 7ra, 23ra, 27rb, 27vb, 28ra, 35ra. - Tämälläs-signs in the shape of a cross (+) indicate the place where the omissions, written in the lower margin, belong: fols. 22vb l.10, 29vb l.17. - A note or a passage omitted in the main text is written, by hand b, in the upper part of <locus target="#19va">fol.  19va</locus>. - Writing exercises: fols. 1rv, 7v, 8r, 14r, 15r, 20vb.</item>
                     </list>
                  </additions>
